sec.p:
Within Neacomys , N. spinosus has the widest distribution, from southern Colombia to northern Bolivia and western Brazil . It inhabits the altitudinal gradient present between Amazonia and the Andes spanning Montane, Pre-Montane, and Rain Forests (
Pacheco et al. 2009
;
Pacheco et al. 2011
) from 300 to 1900 m in elevation ( Leo & Romo 1992 ;
Patton et al. 2000
; Weksler & Bonvicino 2015a ). This species exhibits great morphological variation; for instance, color of dorsal fur varies from reddish to brown (
Patton et al. 2000
; Weksler & Bonvicino 2015a ), ventral fur can be from totally white to grayish ( Thomas 1882 ; Lawrence 1941 ; Weksler 2006 ), tail can be longer than head-body length or they can be same sized ( Lawrence 1941 ), metatarsal patch ranges from being a small tenuous spot to broadly extended ( Lawrence 1941 ), hind feet being smaller in lowland populations than in highland populations ( Lawrence 1941 ), and supraorbital beads of the skull range from moderately developed to strongly developed ( Thomas 1882 ; Lawrence 1941 ).

Taxonomically, four subspecies have been recognized within N. spinosus ( Thomas 1900 ; Thomas 1903 ; Hershkovitz 1940 ; Lawrence 1941 ): N. s.tenuipesThomas, 1900 is found in northern Colombia and is distinguished from spinosus because it presents darker dorsal fur, pure white ventral fur, and shorter and more slender hind feet ( Thomas 1900 ); N. s. amoenus inhabits Brazilian Cerrado, it is larger than spinosus , has a longer tail and braincase, softer and shorter dorsal and ventral fur, and pure white ventral fur ( Thomas 1903 ); N. s. carceleni is found near the Curaray River in Ecuador and differs from spinosus because it has a shorter tail, pure white ventral fur, a longer and heavier braincase, well developed supraorbital ridges, and longer molar rows ( Hershkovitz 1940 ); and N. s. spinosus inhabits along montane cloud forests in Peru , that presents ventral fur with gray bases and large metatarsal patches ( Thomas 1882 , Lawrence 1941 ). From these subspecies, based on morphological characters alone, Lawrence (1941) considered N. tenuipes to be a species, retained N. s. spinosus and N. s. carceleni as subspecies, but dismissed N. s. amoenus from the comparisons entirely. N. tenuipes is molecularly distinct from other congeners, the support of its phylogenetic relationships among Neacomys is weak although is supposed to be closer related to Amazonian species (
Patton et al. 2000
). On the other hand, based on a bibliographic review, Cabrera (1961) recognized three subspecies, that differ each other in their geographical distributions N. s. spinosus , N. s. amoenus , and N. s. carceleni . Currently, N. spinosus with its subspecies amoenus and carceleni is considered as widely distributed species spreading through geographical barriers and different landscapes (
Honacki et al. 1982
; Novak & Paradiso 1983 ; Musser & Carleton 1993 ; Musser & Carleton 2005 ;
Patton et al. 2000
;
Patton et al. 2008
; Weksler & Bonvicino 2015a ).

All sequences were aligned in Clustal W (
Thompson et al. 1994
) by default parameters, and posteriorly reviewed by eye in order to check for frameshifts, indels or stop codons in MEGA 5 (
Tamura et al. 2011
); the matrix was completed with ambiguous state characters (i.e., n). Genetic divergence was determined by calculating p-distances ( MEGA 5,
Tamura et al. 2011
). Substitution model GTR+I+gamma was selected with jModelTest ( Posada 2008 ), by AIC (using the “propose model” routine). In order to recover phylogenetic relationships, we analyzed the sequence matrix by Maximum Likelihood (ML) and Bayesian inference (BI). ML analysis was conducted using the Randomized Accelerated Maximum Likelihood (RAxML) algorithm version 7.0.4 ( Stamatakis 2006 ) with 10,000 bootstrap pseudo-replicates to search for the best tree and bootstrap support (BS). BI analysis was performed with MrBayes 3.2.6 ( Ronquist & Huelsenbeck 2003 ); four simultaneous Markov chains were run for 20,000,000 generations, with a sampling frequency of 1,000 generations. Convergence on a stable loglikelihood value was verified by plotting the log-likelihood values against generation time for each chain. The first 25% of the trees were discarded as burn-in and the remaining trees were used to compute a 50% majority rule consensus tree and to obtain posterior probability (PP) estimates for each clade.

Cranial characters also provide evidence for the distinction of these taxa. For instance, skulls of N. s. spinosus and Neacomys sp. nov. are small size, and N. s. amoenus and N. s. carceleni are large sized ( Table 2 ,
