Molecular evidence. Similar topologies were recovered using both Maximum Likelihood and Bayesian Inference (
). Regarding phylogenetic relationships, Neacomys is recovered as monophyletic group (BS = 71%, PP = 0.99) formed by three clades. We propose that these clades represent groups of species: the “ paracou ” group (BS = 99%, PP = 1.00) which is the sister group of “ spinosus ” group (BS = 99%, PP = 1.00), and “ tenuipes ” group (BS = 70%, PP = 0.93). The “ paracou ” group is monotypic, formed by N. paracou . The “ spinosus ” group is formed by N. spinosus , N. amoenus s.l (BS = 100%, PP = 1.00), and Neacomys sp. nov. (BS = 93%, PP = 1.00). The “ tenuipes ” group is formed by N. tenuipes , N. guianae (BS = 100%, PP = 1.00), Neacomys sp. “clade 3” (BS = 99%, PP = 1.00), N. minutus s.l. (BS = 99%, PP = 1.00), N. musseri (BS = 100%, PP = 1.00), N. dubosti (BS = 100%, PP = 1.00), Neacomys sp. “clade 6” (following
Patton et al. 2000
, BS = 93%, PP = 1.00), and Neacomys sp. “clade 7” (following
Patton et al. 2000
).

