sec.p:
The biogeographic ranges of the species within “ spinosus ” group are distinct. Neacomys spinosus is an endemic species from Peru that inhabits in mountain cloud forests between the southern of Marañon River to the northern of Huallaga River ( Lawrence 1941; this study ). N. vargasllosai sp. nov. inhabits in mountain cloud forests between Peru and Bolivia from the northern of the Inambari River to western Santa Cruz ( Thomas 1901 ;
Pacheco et al. 2011
; this study). Likewise, N. amoenus s.l occurs in the Cerrado between eastern Bolivia and western Brazil , and the Amazon rainforests from southeastern Ecuador to northeastern Peru . Contrasting with the last record of Peruvian mammals (
Pacheco et al. 2009
), we conclude that at least five species of Neacomys are present in Peru ( N. amoenus , N. minutus , N. musseri , N. spinosus , and N. vargasllosai sp. nov. ).

Based on the species’ distributions in the Andes, it is possible that rivers on the eastern slope of the Andes (e.g. Marañón , Huallaga, Apurimac , and Inambari) could have played a role in delimiting the distribution of these species of Neacomys . The role of rivers in the diversification of Andean biota has been previously proposed in birds (e.g.
Ribas et al. 2007
; Weir 2009 ; Bonaccorso 2009 ;
Chaves et al. 2011
, Winger & Bates 2015 ), plants (e.g.
Pennington et al. 2010
;
Särkinen et al. 2012
) and rodents ( Patton & Smith 1992 ). In the case of sigmodontine rodents, Patton & Smith (1992) were the precursors assessing the allopatric role of Andean rivers in the diversification of Akodon ; they recovered reciprocal monophyly between populations without morphological support, suggesting that further taxonomic analysis is needed to support speciation. After the research of Patton & Smith (1992) , recent taxonomic studies invoked the allopatric role of the rivers along the Andes to constrain the distribution of sigmodontine species (e.g. Luna & Pacheco, 2002 ;
Jiménez et al. 2013
;
Pacheco et al. 2014
; Rengifo & Pacheco 2015 ), however some of these studies have failed to use formal methods to assess allopatric speciation or lacks phylogenetic support. In this context, the divergence of Neacomys species in the Andes could be due to the allopatric role of the Andean rivers; however, further analysis is needed to assess whether these rivers were preexisting barriers or not.
